<p>The <code>sandbox</code> tag executes PHP code in an isolated sandbox environment.</p>

<h2>Syntax</h2>
<pre>{open}sandbox 'phpfile'{close}</pre>

<h2>How It Works</h2>
<p>The sandbox tag:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Creates an isolated execution environment</li>
  <li>Executes the specified PHP file</li>
  <li>Limits access to prevent security issues</li>
</ol>

<h2>Comparison: sandbox vs code</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Feature</th><th>sandbox</th><th>code</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Isolated environment</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Variable access</td><td>Limited</td><td>Full</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Security</td><td>Higher</td><td>Standard</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Use case</td><td>Untrusted code</td><td>Trusted code</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>Use Cases</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Execute user-provided code safely</li>
  <li>Run plugins or extensions</li>
  <li>Test code in isolation</li>
  <li>Limit side effects of code execution</li>
</ul>

<h2>Example</h2>
<pre>{open}sandbox 'plugin'{close}</pre>
<p>This would execute plugin.php in a sandboxed environment, limiting its access to system resources.</p>

<h2>Note</h2>
<p>Use sandbox when executing code that may not be fully trusted or when you want to prevent unintended side effects on the main application state.</p>
